cs.LG, cs.NE, cs.AI, cs.HC, cs.SI 

This paper deals with the problem of classification in Brain Computer Interface (BCI) using EEG data. The paper proposes a method to identify and remove artifacts in the data during pre-processing stage, which is a common problem in EEG data analysis. This suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-category of cs.SI (Signal Processing). The paper also proposes an adaptive learning classifier using Joint Approximate Diagonalization (JAD) for multiclass classification, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The use of Self-Regulated Interval Type-2 Neuro-Fuzzy Inference System (SRIT2NFIS) for classification suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper deals with the problem of non-stationarity in the features extracted from the CSP, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction).
